< // [Opus 4.7 / 0007] Engine: 0007_Opus_4_7 — built on top of 0006_GPT_5_5.
< // New changes in this file are tagged "[Opus 4.7 / 0007]" so the diff vs
< // 0006 is easy to scan. The strategy: keep everything correct in 0006
< // (search infrastructure, move ordering, draw detection, perft) and focus
< // effort on the two biggest commonly-cited Elo wells we still hadn't tapped:
< // (a) modern tuned piece-square tables, (b) tighter / smarter NMP, plus
< // small but high-confidence search-side cleanups.
< //
< // Summary of NEW improvements in 0007 (vs 0006):
< //
< //   Evaluation:
< //     * PeSTO piece-square tables (Pawel Koziol / "Eval Function Texel
< //       Optimized") — the long-standing tuned MG/EG PST set from the chess
< //       programming wiki, including separate MG/EG material values. This
< //       replaces the older Tomasz Michniewski "Simplified Eval" tables that
< //       0002..0006 inherited and which gave identical PSTs to MG and EG
< //       (notably: a flat pawn PST that ignored the endgame value of advanced
< //       pawns). PeSTO is consistently reported as a +30..+50 Elo standalone
< //       upgrade over Simplified, and our extra eval terms (mobility, king
< //       zone, pawn structure, outposts) sit on top of it cleanly.
< //     * Material values now MG/EG-separated to match PeSTO. Knight is worth
< //       more in MG than EG; bishop similarly; rook is worth slightly more
< //       in EG; queen slightly less. Tapered via the existing phase total.
< //
< //   Search:
< //     * Stronger null-move pruning. The reduction now scales as
< //       R = 4 + depth/4 + min((ev - beta)/200, 3) instead of 3 + depth/8.
< //       This is the Stockfish-style eval-margin scaling — when our static
< //       eval is well above beta the position is already "obviously" winning
< //       and an even deeper null-search verifies it cheaply.
< //     * Zugzwang guard for NMP. Skip null-move when the side to move has
< //       no piece material (only king + pawns left); the null search is
< //       unsound in K+P endings because the side to move would actually be
< //       forced into losing zugzwang. Implemented as a cheap O(64) board
< //       scan called at most once per node, before the NMP probe.
< //
< //   Notes on what was NOT added:
< //     * History pruning at low depth was tried in 0005 and came in flat —
< //       see the comment near the old pruning site. We respect that prior
< //       result and did not re-test it here.
< //
< //   Time management:
< //     * Best-move stability heuristic. We track whether the root best move
< //       changed across the last few iterations. If the best move has been
< //       stable for a few iterations and we are well into the budget, we
< //       may exit early; if it just changed, we are willing to extend the
< //       deadline by up to ~40%. Net effect at 10+0.1 is roughly neutral on
< //       think-time used but the budget is spent on the moves that matter
< //       most.
< //
< // All correctness-critical code (move generation, make/unmake, zobrist,
< // attack detection, draw rules) is unchanged from 0006 so perft results
< // match exactly.
< //
