< // [Opus 4.7 / 0007] PeSTO piece-square tables. Source: Pawel Koziol's
< // "Eval Function Texel Optimized" (PeSTO) tables as documented on the chess
< // programming wiki (https://www.chessprogramming.org/PeSTO%27s_Evaluation_Function).
< // They were tuned with the Texel method over millions of game positions and
< // are the standard "good baseline" PST set used by most modern HCE engines.
< //
< // Compared to the Simplified Eval tables they replace, the key differences:
< //   * Material is MG/EG-separated (knight/bishop worth more in MG, slightly
< //     less in EG; rook +35 in EG; queen -89 in EG). This is essential for
< //     accurate tapering and was previously a "free" upgrade we hadn't taken.
< //   * Pawn EG is no longer a flat copy of MG — advanced pawns are weighted
< //     up to +178cp on the 7th rank (i.e. an extra ~one pawn of bonus per
< //     rank advanced toward promotion). The Simplified tables ignored this
< //     entirely and relied on our passed-pawn bonus to make up the gap.
< //   * Knight & bishop EG tables prefer the centre for endgame piece activity.
< //   * Rook EG slightly prefers the back ranks (good rook on 7th).
< //   * King MG retains a strong back-rank / corner preference; King EG
< //     pulls the king to the centre for endgame play.
< //
< // Tables are listed in PeSTO's published order: row 0 = rank 8 (black back
< // rank), row 7 = rank 1 (white back rank). The existing initEval index
< // flip then maps to our 0x88 board correctly.
